Low — likely **15–25%**, and here's the honest reasoning:

**The math works against you:**
- If each roadmap item has an 80% individual completion probability (optimistic), five items compound to ~33%. Ten items drops to ~11%.
- "Every item" is a conjunction — any single miss invalidates success.

**Two strong weeks is a weak signal:**
- Two weeks is ~15% of a quarter. Early momentum is common; sustained momentum through crunch, dependencies, and scope creep is not.
- Motivated teams frequently underestimate the back half of a quarter when real complexity surfaces.

**Quality slipping is a lagging indicator:**
- Teams under deadline pressure often ship features but accumulate technical debt or skip edge-case testing. The quality cost may not be visible until after the quarter ends.

**What would move the probability up:**
- Roadmap is already 60%+ complete with only polish remaining
- Zero external dependencies (no waiting on other teams, APIs, approvals)
- Explicit scope has been cut and agreed upon — not just hoped to be manageable
- Definition of "quality" is written down, not assumed

**Bottom line:** Two good weeks and team energy are necessary but not sufficient. Unless your roadmap is small, well-scoped, and already partially shipped, treat this as a 1-in-5 outcome, not a near-certainty.
